00:02.545 --> 00:14.102
This is an interview with area court director 
Frank Keenan by Lisa Walker on the 23rd of

00:02.545 --> 00:14.102
November, 1989, at the Hidalgo International 
Bridge concerning the war on drugs. In the

00:15.303 --> 00:23.575
interest of accumulating knowledge, I'm asking 
you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas A&M Oral

00:15.303 --> 00:23.575
History Collection at the University Archives. 
Is that OK with you? Yes. It's quite OK. Great.

00:29.849 --> 00:32.572
First of all, I'd like to hear a little bit about 
yourself. What's your personal background and

00:32.592 --> 00:37.277
education? Well, I grew up in Detroit, Michigan. 
I'm a graduate of Wayne State University. I have a

00:45.466 --> 00:50.912
master's degree from Eastern Michigan 
University. I've been in customs since 1965. I was

00:55.458 --> 00:59.502
an inspector in Detroit. In 1972, I went to 
headquarters and was there, except for a couple of

01:01.102 --> 01:10.697
overseas assignments. I was there continuously 
until about 1985. And I was an operations officer

01:13.782 --> 01:19.490
in Houston, Texas. And I've been here for the last 
two years as a port director.

01:27.723 --> 01:27.984
Wow. You've worked all over the place. Okay, let's 
get started. First of all, I'd like to ask you, what

01:33.786 --> 01:46.198
was the Customs Service's role in the war on drugs 
through the different administrations,

01:33.786 --> 01:46.198
starting with Carter and ending with President? 
Well, my involvement in the war on drugs really

01:46.218 --> 01:50.142
started in 1973. That was when President Nixon 
began to take a look and saw that United States was

01:59.219 --> 02:13.177
having a major drug problem and every president 
since then has tried to commit resources to some

01:59.219 --> 02:13.177
kind of war on drugs.

02:15.981 --> 02:18.584
Do you want to know what our role is? Yes sir. 
Customs is only one of many agencies involved in

02:18.784 --> 02:22.549
this. We see the war on drugs as a multi agency 
multinational operation customs is

02:28.042 --> 02:56.462
trying to control have jurisdiction on the 
borders airports and seaports at the ports of

02:28.042 --> 02:56.462
entry themselves when one gets away from the ports 
of entry that it becomes under the jurisdiction of

02:28.042 --> 02:56.462
border patrol the Drug Enforcement 
Administration, and other local and federal

02:58.535 --> 03:05.946
agencies. They're only really a small part of the 
total . And has that role changed through the

03:11.333 --> 03:16.661
administrations, or has it changed? I haven't 
seen any change at all from one administration to

03:16.681 --> 03:23.170
the other. There was a slight difference between 
the Nixon and Carter administrations I think

03:28.302 --> 03:58.123
maybe enforcement was downplayed somewhat 
during the Carter administration and then picked

03:28.302 --> 03:58.123
up again quite dramatically at least the at least 
verbally under Reagan and then it's continued

03:28.302 --> 03:58.123
under Bush I haven't seen any difference at all 
between the Reagan administration and Bush

03:28.302 --> 03:58.123
administration except that President Bush has 
done what other presidents have tried to do, and

03:59.757 --> 04:19.919
that is to appoint somebody to be in charge of the 
total operation,

03:59.757 --> 04:19.919
Mr. Bennett. But we haven't actually seen any

04:19.939 --> 04:26.205
action from that office yet. I think things are 
still in the planning stage. They haven't

04:29.255 --> 04:34.701
actually implemented what he has planned. Oh, you 
were reading my mind. That was my next question. It

04:36.944 --> 04:43.291
was about the drug czar and if that's cut down and 
the overlapping of duties between the agencies. I

04:43.311 --> 04:44.453
haven't seen any difference. We're still turf 
conscious, unfortunately. But it hasn't

04:51.241 --> 04:52.282
changed. I worked between 1973 and about 1985 I 
worked overseas a good part of my time with other

05:00.001 --> 05:05.629
agencies, DEA. A lot of the agents, DEA agents I 
worked with overseas were formal customs agents.

05:13.501 --> 05:16.926
And there was always rivalry then. There's 
rivalry now. I hope that Bennett can change that,

05:21.292 --> 05:27.441
because I think it's really counterproductive. 
My attitude is... My personal attitude is that I

05:29.532 --> 05:37.322
don't care who stops it as long as it's stopped. And 
I'm perfectly happy to see DEA take the credit or

05:37.342 --> 05:41.948
Border Patrol or anybody else. Unfortunately, 
very

05:43.450 --> 05:50.760
few law enforcement officers feel that way. They 
want the credit for themselves, and they don't

05:50.780 --> 05:56.147
want to share it. I understand wanting credit when 
credit is needed. It's possible that Bennett,

06:00.099 --> 06:09.529
once we begin to implement these strategies and 
plans, it may be this way.

06:12.072 --> 06:14.294
And I hope that. OK. Coming onto somewhat of a 
different subject, the VA chief, John Laws, was

06:14.314 --> 06:26.607
quoted in a time magazine as saying, we want to talk 
about slowing down the flow of cocaine into the

06:14.314 --> 06:26.607
United States. we should think more in terms of 
demand reduction. Now, besides the zero

06:30.715 --> 06:40.504
tolerance policy, how is Customs approaching the 
demand reduction,

06:30.715 --> 06:40.504
actually? Or as Customs? Well, we're acting on 
behalf of the United States government in other

06:40.824 --> 06:50.933
areas besides enforcement.

06:50.953 --> 06:56.998
Our officers in every court, in every district 
probably in this country, go out on their own time

06:58.919 --> 07:06.430
and on government time and talk to school children 
of all ages. We've instituted a program where we

07:08.393 --> 07:25.498
talk to, first of all, the students to try to 
reinforce the general perception that they

07:08.393 --> 07:25.498
should stay away from drugs. We do about the same as 
the other agencies in that respect. We also have a

07:30.003 --> 07:47.941
program that's

07:30.003 --> 07:47.941
asking American citizens and residents of the 
United States to help us in the drug war by

07:30.003 --> 07:47.941
reporting anything that they think might be drug 
related. If they see something suspicious, an

07:49.903 --> 07:57.951
airplane unloading in a remote airfield, and look 
suspicious in a boat in some harbor or someplace,

07:58.353 --> 08:06.501
then if they think it's drugs, then they have a 
responsibility, we think. And we encourage them

08:06.581 --> 08:08.523
to call us and tell us. And we'll dispatch 
immediately officers and equipment to the area to

08:09.664 --> 08:17.172
try to intercept it. Is that the B alert? That's the 
B alert, yes. There are rewards for that.

08:24.118 --> 08:26.841
Generally, the attitude we've taken is, I've had 
it for a long time, and I think we take it as a

08:28.424 --> 08:31.468
service. We believe that we can't do it by 
ourselves. We can't seal off the borders. We can't

08:40.640 --> 08:51.173
stand hand in hand across the whole Mexican border 
and also across the seaports and airports and so

08:40.640 --> 08:51.173
on. It's impossible. The only way we're ever going 
to stop this is to...

09:01.955 --> 09:03.017
stop the demand. And that takes everybody. 
Everybody has to be involved in that, not only the

09:05.501 --> 09:09.167
small part of it. Parents have to warn their kids 
against drugs. Brothers have to warn their little

09:13.875 --> 09:18.423
sisters and brothers against drugs and so on. 
Everybody has to be involved. I don't see that

09:20.847 --> 09:25.515
happening in the

09:20.847 --> 09:25.515
near future. Going back to zero tolerance, zero 
tolerance, as I understand it, is the policy of

09:26.896 --> 09:37.932
arresting any person and or seizing his property 
that brings in any amount of illegal drugs. Is this

09:38.753 --> 09:42.118
policy still enforced, and is it effective? Well, 
it's not exactly as you describe it. It never has

09:45.483 --> 09:46.345
been. Zero tolerance is an attempt to

09:47.707 --> 09:56.059
make of illegal drugs in any quantities 
responsible for their illegal action. Somebody

10:06.549 --> 10:13.539
who smokes marijuana is doing it illegally. 
Whether it's one ounce or half an ounce or a gram or

10:13.559 --> 10:20.468
whether it's a ton, it's illegal. Zero tolerance 
simply means that if we find it, and we will seize

10:27.157 --> 10:39.134
the conveyance in which it was transported, in 
most cases as an automobile or an airplane or a

10:27.157 --> 10:39.134
boat.

10:40.076 --> 10:54.396
In recent months, if the person who owns the 
vehicle

10:40.076 --> 10:54.396
has no knowledge, if he can satisfy the government 
that He didn't know the person who had the drugs

10:55.557 --> 11:00.563
actually had it. He was not responsible, such as a 
rental agency, or if a parent lets a son or daughter

11:00.803 --> 11:17.543
take a car, or if they take it without permission, 
if obviously they can't control them 24 hours a

11:00.803 --> 11:17.543
day. There are provisions that the property, that 
is the conveyance, is returned to the owner. but

11:25.730 --> 11:27.973
not without penalty. We think that by we, I mean the 
government. The United States Customs Service

11:31.919 --> 11:36.726
did not invent zero tolerance. We didn't make it 
up. We only enforced it because we were told to

11:38.128 --> 11:42.915
right down from the White House. We're an arm of the 
executive branch of government. We do what we're

11:48.643 --> 11:51.106
told. And we do it with as much energy as we can. And 
when they say it's against the law to bring in any

11:55.767 --> 12:06.362
measurable amount of drugs in the United States, 
and if we find it, then we're going to have to bring

11:55.767 --> 12:06.362
it along. And do you see any changes between Reagan 
and Bush in the disenforcement policy? No, I don't

12:15.135 --> 12:16.237
think so. I think Bush

12:16.297 --> 12:22.466
is just as strong against it. As I said before, it 
It's not a criminal, in most cases, a criminal

12:25.720 --> 12:29.284
proceeding. Serial tolerance, at least the 
current interpretation of it, is a monetary

12:30.245 --> 12:47.424
penalty in lieu of seizing the conveyance. We may 
hold up the conveyance for a while, but in most

